Diathermy device
We used a commercially available electrosurgery unit (Itkacut 350MB, Innokas Medical, Fin-
land) set at a nominal 120 Wpower. Such a high power level was used to avoid the sample
sticking to the diathermy tip. We used direct cut settings at a cutting frequency of 450 kHz.
We made a flat, steel custom-ground electrode (19 x 19 cm) for the robot stage, and measured
the cutting voltage at slightly under 800 V peak-to-peak.
Samples
The test materials were fresh, (unfrozen) Finnish landrace porcine tissues, purchased froma
local slaughterhouse (Paijan Tilateurastamo, Urjala, Finland). The smoke fromten different
tissue types was measured: skeletal muscle, liver, subcutaneous fat, renal pelvis, renal cortex,
lung, bronchus, cerebral gray and white matter, and skin, all taken fromthe same animal. We
performed the sampling with the automated xyz-stage to ensure that the cuts were all the same
size. A typical cutting pattern is presented in
